SIMPLE: traverse
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Traverse
<hw>Trav"erse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>travers</ets>, L. <ets>transversus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>transvertere</ets> to turn or direct across. See
<er>Transverse</er>, and cf. <er>Travers</er>.]</ety> <def>Lying across;
being in a direction across something else; <as>as, paths cut with
<ex>traverse</ex> trenches</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oak . . . being strong in all positions, may be better trusted in
cross and <qex>traverse</qex> work.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ridges of the fallow field <qex>traverse</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hayward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Traverse drill</b></col> <fld>(Mach.)</fld>, <cd>a
machine tool for drilling slots, in which the work or tool has a lateral
motion back and forth; also, a drilling machine in which the spindle
holder can be adjusted laterally.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traverse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Traverse
<hw>Trav"erse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>Athwart; across;
crosswise.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traverse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Traverse
<hw>Trav"erse</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>traverse</ets>. See
<er>Traverse</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything that
traverses, or crosses.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>Something that thwarts, crosses, or obstructs; a
cross accident; as, he would have succeeded, had it not been for unlucky
<xex>traverses</xex> not under his control.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>A barrier, sliding door, movable screen, curtain,
or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men drinken and the <qex>travers</qex> draw anon.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the entrance of the king,⟦br⟧
The first <qex>traverse</qex> was drawn.</q> <rj><qau>F.
Beaumont.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A gallery or loft of
communication from side to side of a church or other large
building.</def> <rj><au>Gwilt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <fld>(Fort.)</fld> <def>A work thrown up to intercept an
enfilade, or reverse fire, along exposed passage, or line of
work.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(e)</sd> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A formal denial of some matter of
fact alleged by the opposite party in any stage of the pleadings. The
technical words introducing a <xex>traverse</xex> are <xex>absque
hoc</xex>, without this; that is, without this which follows.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(f)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The zigzag course or courses
made by a ship in passing from one place to another; a compound
course.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(g)</sd> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A line lying across a figure or
other lines; a transversal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(h)</sd> <fld>(Surv.)</fld> <def>A line surveyed across a plot of
ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(i)</sd> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>The turning of a gun so as to
make it point in any desired direction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A turning; a trick; a subterfuge.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To work a traverse</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To
solve a traverse</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to reduce a
series of courses or distances to an equivalent single one; to calculate
the resultant of a traverse.</cd> -- <col><b>Traverse board</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a small board hung in the steerage, having the
points of the compass marked on it, and for each point as many holes as
there are half hours in a watch. It is used for recording the courses
made by the ship in each half hour, by putting a peg in the
corresponding hole.</cd> -- <col><b>Traverse jury</b></col>
<fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a jury that tries cases; a petit jury.</cd> --
<col><b>Traverse sailing</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a sailing by
compound courses; the method or process of finding the resulting course
and distance from a series of different shorter courses and distances
actually passed over by a ship.</cd> -- <col><b>Traverse
table</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Naut. & Surv.)</fld> <cd>A table by
means of which the difference of latitude and departure corresponding to
any given course and distance may be found by inspection. It contains
the lengths of the two sides of a right-angled triangle, usually for
every quarter of a degree of angle, and for lengths of the hypothenuse,
from 1 to 100.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Railroad)</fld> <cd>A platform
with one or more tracks, and arranged to move laterally on wheels, for
shifting cars, etc., from one line of track to another.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traverse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Traverse
<hw>Trav"erse</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Traversed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Traversing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>traverser</ets>.
See <er>Traverse</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To lay in a
cross direction; to cross.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The parts should be often <qex>traversed</qex>, or crossed, by the
flowing of the folds.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cross by way of opposition; to thwart with
obstacles; to obstruct; to bring to naught.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I can not but . . . admit the force of this reasoning, which I yet
hope to <qex>traverse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To wander over; to cross in traveling; <as>as, to
<ex>traverse</ex> the habitable globe</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What seas you <qex>traversed</qex>, and what fields you
fought.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pass over and view; to survey
carefully.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My purpose is to <qex>traverse</qex> the nature, principles, and
properties of this detestable vice -- ingratitude.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Gun.)</fld> <def>To turn to the one side or the
other, in order to point in any direction; <as>as, to <ex>traverse</ex>
a cannon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Carp.)</fld> <def>To plane in a direction across
the grain of the wood; <as>as, to <ex>traverse</ex> a
board</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To deny formally, as what the
opposite party has alleged. When the plaintiff or defendant advances new
matter, he avers it to be true, and <xex>traverses</xex> what the other
party has affirmed. To <xex>traverse</xex> an indictment or an office is
to deny it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And save the expense of long litigious laws,⟦br⟧
Where suits are <qex>traversed</qex>, and so little won⟦br⟧
That he who conquers is but last undone.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To traverse a yard</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
brace it fore and aft.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traverse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Traverse
<hw>Trav"erse</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
use the posture or motions of opposition or counteraction, as in
fencing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To see thee fight, to see thee foin, to see thee
<qex>traverse</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn, as on a pivot; to move round; to swivel;
<as>as, the needle of a compass <ex>traverses</ex>; if it does not
<ex>traverse</ex> well, it is an unsafe guide.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tread or move crosswise, as a horse that throws
his croup to one side and his head to the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Traverse drill</ent>⟦br⟧
